 Tom Jenkins","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"FA Cup: talking points from the weekend's action | Guardian writers","webPublicationDate":"2014-02-17T09:00:02Z","sectionName":"Football","sectionId":"football","id":"football/blog/2014/feb/17/fa-cup-talking-points-football","fields":{"hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<h2>1) Fourth choice good enough to beat Chelsea</h2><p>Stevan Jovetic scored Manchester City's opener against Chelsea with a neat finish off a post and then bridled when told that José Mourinho had branded him the fourth choice striker.</p><p>\"He said that? That is maybe his opinion but of course I started late because I was injured so many times. What is important is that I was calm. I know my own value, and know I will play very well, and score more goals,\" came Jovetic's response.</p><p>The Montenegrin has become too familiar with the club's medical staff in this debut season following a £22m move from Fiorentina in the summer. Yet as his reply to Mourinho indicates, self-confidence remains intact and a glance at his disrupted campaign shows there have still been four goals in 11 City appearances (plus two more for Montenegro). These are hardly shabby numbers and with Jovetic accustomed to playing in any of the forward positions the 24-year-old may yet prove invaluable to City and illustrate his quality in the final third of the season. <strong>Jamie Jackson </strong></p><p><blockquote>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/15/manchester-city-chelsea-fa-cup\" title=\"\">Match report: Manchester City 2-0 Chelsea</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/15/manchester-city-pellegrini-chelsea-fa-cup-mourinho\" title=\"\">Paul Wilson: Pellegrini stalls Chelsea momentum</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/jose-mourinho-manchester-city-chelsea-fa-cup\" title=\"\">Mourinho admits City were the better team</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/manchester-city-barcelona-chelsea-champions-league\" title=\"\">• Pellegrini: City are ready for Barça</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/jesus-navas-manchester-city-barcelona-champions-league\" title=\"\">• Navas: Messi won't be happy coming to City</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/barcelona-pedro-champions-league-manchester-city\" title=\"\">• Big interview: Sid Lowe talks to Barcelona's Pedro</a></blockquote></p><p></p><h2>2) Webb must up his game for Brazil</h2><p>It was a good night for World Cup-bound Englishmen at the Emirates. Well, for some of them anyway. Alex Oxlade-Chamberlain confirmed his recent progress, scoring one and making one and producing a performance of speed, intelligence and a very English kind of all-action vim. Raheem Sterling was again impressive and Steven Gerrard dominant in the second half in his withdrawn midfield role. Carl Jenkinson, always good when he's facing forwards, less so when asked to turn and defend the space behind him, had a good game at right back for Arsenal. Daniel Sturridge didn't score but radiated a well-seasoned menace.</p><p>And then, of course, there was Howard Webb, who will also be in Brazil, who has endured a difficult start to the year, and who was again decisively below par. Webb should have given Liverpool a game-changing second penalty after Oxlade-Chamberlain had barged Luis Suárez to the ground in the second half. He should have given Steven Gerrard a second yellow card. He allowed a horrible challenge by Lukas Podolski to stand unpunished. And he generally refereed the match with the familiar sense of strutting, celebrified conviction that is just about bearable when he gets the majority of his decisions right, but which can grate horribly when he's off his game.</p><p>There were some misguided calls after the game for referees to appear in public to explain their decisions at the final whistle. In practice it is hard to imagine anything more grisly. Referees, who should be half-seen and certainly not heard, have for some time seemed confused enough over the exact extent and reach of their role, apparently elevated in their own minds to something only marginally beneath the players themselves. An out-of-form Englishman in a World Cup year is an all-too familiar story. Webb needs to up his game, soft-pedal a little his relentlessly insistent on-field persona, and simply get a few more of the big decisions right. <strong>Barney Ronay</strong></p><p><blockquote><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/brendan-rodgers-liverpool-arsenal-fa-cup\" title=\"\">• Rodgers fumes over 'blatant' penalty</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/arsenal-liverpool-fa-cup-match-report\" title=\"\">• Match report: Arsenal 2-1 Liverpool</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/feb/16/arsenal-liverpool-fa-cup-fifth-round\" title=\"\">• Barney Ronay: Arsenal find the way to revenge</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/liverpool-steven-gerrard-holding-role-arsenal\" title=\"\">• Michael Cox: Gerrard can thrive in holding role</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/feb/16/arsenal-liverpool-fa-cup-talking-points\" title=\"\">• Paul Doyle: five talking points from the Emirates</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/gallery/2014/feb/16/fa-cup-arsenal\" title=\"\">• Tom Jenkins's best images from the Emirates</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/arsene-wenger-jose-mourinho-silly-disrespectful\" title=\"\">• Wenger brands Mourinho as 'silly and disrespectful'</a></blockquote></p><p></p><h2>3) Four won't go into three and certainly won't fit into two</h2><p>We are talking Sunderland's central midfield. Gus Poyet has his problems on Wearside – after all his team are in the Premier League's bottom three as well as the Capital One Cup final and the FA Cup quarter finals – but right now he possesses an embarrassment of riches in the heart of midfield.</p><p>With Liam Bridcutt, the manager's favourite holding midfielder, Lee Cattermole – excellent against Southampton when Bridcutt was rested – Jack Colback and Ki Sung-yueng all in sparkling form, which trio should play in the engine room of his hallmark 4-1-4-1 formation?</p><p>And what if Poyet opts to repeat his successful experiment with 4-1-3-2 that worked pretty well against Southmampton? Which two out of Bridcutt, Cattermole, Colback and Ki would he then drop? Oh and let's not forget that Craig Gardner, yet another Sunderland central midfielder, shone on Saturday not only scoring the winner but persistently getting behind Maurcio Pochettino's defence after making dangerous late runs from deep. While Gardner's touch is less than velvet his shooting from distance tends to be unerring. For Poyet it seems very much a case of dilemmas, dilemmas. If only he had a quartet – or even quintet – of prolific strikers to ponder. <strong>Louise Taylor </strong></p><p><blockquote>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/15/sunderland-southampton-fa-cup-match-report\" title=\"\">Match report: Sunderland 1-0 Southampton </a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/15/sunderland-southampton-live-fa-cup-report\" title=\"\">Minute-by-minute report: look back on all the key events</a></blockquote></p><p></p><h2>4) If only Solskjaer was a few years younger</h2><p>The fact that Cardiff struggled to score against Championship opposition on Saturday is symptomatic of their season – 19 goals in 26 Premier League matches says it all. At the other end of the pitch only Fulham have conceded more than the 44 goals Cardiff have shipped. It is a dangerous combination and one which will see Cardiff relegated unless Ole Gunnar Solskjaer can find a remedy. While the sort of defensive mistakes that contributed to Wigan opening the scoring can be ironed out on the training ground, it is questionable how much Cardiff's manager can do about their goal threat. Fraizer Campbell, Cardiff's leading scorer with eight in all competitions, has never been prolific at the top level. Kenwyne Jones, signed from Stoke in January, is a one-in-four man. All of which means Cardiff need to rely on goals from other areas – a big ask when Jordan Mutch is their second highest Premier League scorer with four and Steven Caulker and Peter Whittingham are tied for third place with two each. Wilfried Zaha and Mats Daehli were brought in to inject some attacking flair but the worry for Cardiff is that they lack the potent goalscorer to make the most of their creativity. If only Solskjaer was a few years younger. <strong>Stuart James</strong></p><p><blockquote>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/15/cardiff-city-wigan-athletic-fa-cup-match-report\" title=\"\">Match report: Cardiff 1-2 Wigan</a></blockquote></p><p></p><h2>5) Harsh to condemn Monk for his team selection at Everton </h2><p>Making eight changes for a fifth-round FA Cup tie and losing 3-1 usually leaves a manager wide open to criticism of demeaning the oldest cup competition in the world. Those allegations were thrown at Swansea City's new manager Garry Monk at Everton. Given the home side's laboured first-half performance maybe an opportunity to reach the quarter-finals for the first time since 1964, and defeat Everton for the first time in Swansea's history, was missed. But the visiting display was not undermined by the change in personnel, only by individual defensive errors that allowed Everton to ultimately ease into the quarter-finals. With Napoli to come and Premier League status paramount, Monk had to utilise his resources. <strong>Andy Hunter</strong></p><p><blockquote>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/everton-fa-cup-swansea-city-match-report\" title=\"\">Match report: Everton 3-1 Swansea</a></blockquote></p><p></p><h2>6) Wembley, and potential derby, rouse Sheffield</h2><p>If Sheffield Wednesday beat Charlton in their FA Cup fifth round tie, Sheffield will be guaranteed a club at Wembley in the semi-finals which, at long last, will provide this city with some success. Both traditionally top flight clubs, Sheffields Wednesday and United have both spent time in England's third tier, giving supporters of both clubs little to cheer. United's biggest game of the season attracted a crowd of 25,118, suggesting the magic of the Cup is very match alive in this part of the world. But there will not be a spare seat in the house at Bramall Lane if the dream Sheffield derby comes to fruition.<strong> Ian Baker</strong></p><p><blockquote>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/16/sheffield-united-nottingham-forest-fa-cup\" title=\"\">Match report: Sheffield United 3-1 Nottingham Forest</a></blockquote></p><p></p><p></p><p>Jason Cairnduff/Action, Adam Davy/PA, Lee Smith/Action, Stu Forster/Getty, Paul Thomas/Getty,</p>","headline":"FA Cup: talking points from the weekend's action","trailText":"<strong>Guardian writers:</strong> Stevan Jovetic comes out swinging, Howard Webb must up his game and Cardiff are craving Ole Gunnar Solskjaer in his pomp","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mnpk","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Pix/pictures/2014/2/17/1392606513667/FA-Cup-talking-points-com-003.jpg","wordcount":"1313","liveBloggingNow":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/feb/17/fa-cup-talking-points-football","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/football/blog/2014/feb/17/fa-cup-talking-points-football","tags":[{"id":"football/fa-cup","webTitle":"FA Cup","type":"keyword","sectionId":"football","sectionName":"Football","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/football/fa-cup","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/football/fa-cup","references":[{"type":"pa-football-competition","id":"pa-football-competition/300"}]},{"id":"football/football","webTitle":"Footb